11423 static void handleOpenCLNoSVMAttr(Sema &S, Decl *D, const ParsedAttr &AL) {
11424  if (S.LangOpts.getOpenCLCompatibleVersion() < 200)
11425  S.Diag(AL.getLoc(), diag::err_attribute_requires_opencl_version)
11426  << AL << "2.0" << 1;
11427  else
11428  S.Diag(AL.getLoc(), diag::warn_opencl_attr_deprecated_ignored)
11429  << AL << S.LangOpts.getOpenCLVersionString();
11430 }

11432 static void handleOpenCLAccessAttr(Sema &S, Decl *D, const ParsedAttr &AL) {
11433  if (D->isInvalidDecl())
11434  return;
11435 
11436  // Check if there is only one access qualifier.
11437  if (D->hasAttr<OpenCLAccessAttr>()) {
11438  if (D->getAttr<OpenCLAccessAttr>()->getSemanticSpelling() ==
11439  AL.getSemanticSpelling()) {
11440  S.Diag(AL.getLoc(), diag::warn_duplicate_declspec)
11441  << AL.getAttrName()->getName() << AL.getRange();
11442  } else {
11443  S.Diag(AL.getLoc(), diag::err_opencl_multiple_access_qualifiers)
11444  << D->getSourceRange();
11445  D->setInvalidDecl(true);
11446  return;
11447  }
11448  }
11449 
11450  // OpenCL v2.0 s6.6 - read_write can be used for image types to specify that
11451  // an image object can be read and written. OpenCL v2.0 s6.13.6 - A kernel
11452  // cannot read from and write to the same pipe object. Using the read_write
11453  // (or __read_write) qualifier with the pipe qualifier is a compilation error.
11454  // OpenCL v3.0 s6.8 - For OpenCL C 2.0, or with the
11455  // __opencl_c_read_write_images feature, image objects specified as arguments
11456  // to a kernel can additionally be declared to be read-write.
11457  // C++ for OpenCL 1.0 inherits rule from OpenCL C v2.0.
11458  // C++ for OpenCL 2021 inherits rule from OpenCL C v3.0.
11459  if (const auto *PDecl = dyn_cast<ParmVarDecl>(D)) {
11460  const Type *DeclTy = PDecl->getType().getCanonicalType().getTypePtr();
11461  if (AL.getAttrName()->getName().contains("read_write")) {
11462  bool ReadWriteImagesUnsupported =
11463  (S.getLangOpts().getOpenCLCompatibleVersion() < 200) ||
11464  (S.getLangOpts().getOpenCLCompatibleVersion() == 300 &&
11465  !S.getOpenCLOptions().isSupported("__opencl_c_read_write_images",
11466  S.getLangOpts()));
11467  if (ReadWriteImagesUnsupported || DeclTy->isPipeType()) {
11468  S.Diag(AL.getLoc(), diag::err_opencl_invalid_read_write)
11469  << AL << PDecl->getType() << DeclTy->isImageType();
11470  D->setInvalidDecl(true);
11471  return;
11472  }
11473  }
11474  }
11475 
11476  D->addAttr(::new (S.Context) OpenCLAccessAttr(S.Context, AL));
11477 }
11478 
11479 static void handleZeroCallUsedRegsAttr(Sema &S, Decl *D, const ParsedAttr &AL) {
11480  // Check that the argument is a string literal.
11481  StringRef KindStr;
11482  SourceLocation LiteralLoc;
11483  if (!S.checkStringLiteralArgumentAttr(AL, 0, KindStr, &LiteralLoc))
11484  return;
11485 
11486  ZeroCallUsedRegsAttr::ZeroCallUsedRegsKind Kind;
11487  if (!ZeroCallUsedRegsAttr::ConvertStrToZeroCallUsedRegsKind(KindStr, Kind)) {
11488  S.Diag(LiteralLoc, diag::warn_attribute_type_not_supported)
11489  << AL << KindStr;
11490  return;
11491  }
11492 
11493  D->dropAttr<ZeroCallUsedRegsAttr>();
11494  D->addAttr(ZeroCallUsedRegsAttr::Create(S.Context, Kind, AL));
11495 }
11496 
11497 static const RecordDecl *GetEnclosingNamedOrTopAnonRecord(const FieldDecl *FD) {
11498  const auto *RD = FD->getParent();
11499  // An unnamed struct is anonymous struct only if it's not instantiated.
11500  // However, the struct may not be fully processed yet to determine
11501  // whether it's anonymous or not. In that case, this function treats it as
11502  // an anonymous struct and tries to find a named parent.
11503  while (RD && (RD->isAnonymousStructOrUnion() ||
11504  (!RD->isCompleteDefinition() && RD->getName().empty()))) {
11505  const auto *Parent = dyn_cast<RecordDecl>(RD->getParent());
11506  if (!Parent)
11507  break;
11508  RD = Parent;
11509  }
11510  return RD;
11511 }
11512 
11513 static bool
11514 CheckCountExpr(Sema &S, FieldDecl *FD, Expr *E,
11515  llvm::SmallVectorImpl<TypeCoupledDeclRefInfo> &Decls) {
11516  if (FD->getParent()->isUnion()) {
11517  S.Diag(FD->getBeginLoc(), diag::err_counted_by_attr_in_union)
11518  << FD->getSourceRange();
11519  return true;
11520  }
11521 
11522  if (!E->getType()->isIntegerType() || E->getType()->isBooleanType()) {
11523  S.Diag(E->getBeginLoc(), diag::err_counted_by_attr_argument_not_integer)
11524  << E->getSourceRange();
11525  return true;
11526  }
11527 
11528  LangOptions::StrictFlexArraysLevelKind StrictFlexArraysLevel =
11529  LangOptions::StrictFlexArraysLevelKind::IncompleteOnly;
11530 
11531  if (!Decl::isFlexibleArrayMemberLike(S.getASTContext(), FD, FD->getType(),
11532  StrictFlexArraysLevel, true)) {
11533  // The "counted_by" attribute must be on a flexible array member.
11534  SourceRange SR = FD->getLocation();
11535  S.Diag(SR.getBegin(),
11536  diag::err_counted_by_attr_not_on_flexible_array_member)
11537  << SR;
11538  return true;
11539  }
11540 
11541  auto *DRE = dyn_cast<DeclRefExpr>(E);
11542  if (!DRE) {
11543  S.Diag(E->getBeginLoc(),
11544  diag::err_counted_by_attr_only_support_simple_decl_reference)
11545  << E->getSourceRange();
11546  return true;
11547  }
11548 
11549  auto *CountDecl = DRE->getDecl();
11550  FieldDecl *CountFD = dyn_cast<FieldDecl>(CountDecl);
11551  if (auto *IFD = dyn_cast<IndirectFieldDecl>(CountDecl)) {
11552  CountFD = IFD->getAnonField();
11553  }
11554  if (!CountFD) {
11555  S.Diag(E->getBeginLoc(), diag::err_counted_by_must_be_in_structure)
11556  << CountDecl << E->getSourceRange();
11557 
11558  S.Diag(CountDecl->getBeginLoc(),
11559  diag::note_flexible_array_counted_by_attr_field)
11560  << CountDecl << CountDecl->getSourceRange();
11561  return true;
11562  }
11563 
11564  if (FD->getParent() != CountFD->getParent()) {
11565  if (CountFD->getParent()->isUnion()) {
11566  S.Diag(CountFD->getBeginLoc(), diag::err_counted_by_attr_refer_to_union)
11567  << CountFD->getSourceRange();
11568  return true;
11569  }
11570  // Whether CountRD is an anonymous struct is not determined at this
11571  // point. Thus, an additional diagnostic in case it's not anonymous struct
11572  // is done later in `Parser::ParseStructDeclaration`.
11573  auto *RD = GetEnclosingNamedOrTopAnonRecord(FD);
11574  auto *CountRD = GetEnclosingNamedOrTopAnonRecord(CountFD);
11575 
11576  if (RD != CountRD) {
11577  S.Diag(E->getBeginLoc(),
11578  diag::err_flexible_array_count_not_in_same_struct)
11579  << CountFD << E->getSourceRange();
11580  S.Diag(CountFD->getBeginLoc(),
11581  diag::note_flexible_array_counted_by_attr_field)
11582  << CountFD << CountFD->getSourceRange();
11583  return true;
11584  }
11585  }
11586 
11587  Decls.push_back(TypeCoupledDeclRefInfo(CountFD, /*IsDref*/ false));
11588  return false;
11589 }
11590 
11591 static void handleCountedByAttrField(Sema &S, Decl *D, const ParsedAttr &AL) {
11592  auto *FD = dyn_cast<FieldDecl>(D);
11593  assert(FD);
11594 
11595  auto *CountExpr = AL.getArgAsExpr(0);
11596  if (!CountExpr)
11597  return;
11598 
11599  llvm::SmallVector<TypeCoupledDeclRefInfo, 1> Decls;
11600  if (CheckCountExpr(S, FD, CountExpr, Decls))
11601  return;
11602 
11603  QualType CAT = S.BuildCountAttributedArrayType(FD->getType(), CountExpr);
11604  FD->setType(CAT);
11605 }

11607 static void handleFunctionReturnThunksAttr(Sema &S, Decl *D,
11608  const ParsedAttr &AL) {
11609  StringRef KindStr;
11610  SourceLocation LiteralLoc;
11611  if (!S.checkStringLiteralArgumentAttr(AL, 0, KindStr, &LiteralLoc))
11612  return;
11613 
11614  FunctionReturnThunksAttr::Kind Kind;
11615  if (!FunctionReturnThunksAttr::ConvertStrToKind(KindStr, Kind)) {
11616  S.Diag(LiteralLoc, diag::warn_attribute_type_not_supported)
11617  << AL << KindStr;
11618  return;
11619  }
11620  // FIXME: it would be good to better handle attribute merging rather than
11621  // silently replacing the existing attribute, so long as it does not break
11622  // the expected codegen tests.
11623  D->dropAttr<FunctionReturnThunksAttr>();
11624  D->addAttr(FunctionReturnThunksAttr::Create(S.Context, Kind, AL));
11625 }

11629  if (!ET)
11630  return false;

11633  return Attr->getType() == SYCLTypeAttr::aspect;
11634 
11635  return false;

11638 SYCLDeviceHasAttr *Sema::MergeSYCLDeviceHasAttr(Decl *D,
11639  const SYCLDeviceHasAttr &A) {
11640  if (const auto *ExistingAttr = D->getAttr<SYCLDeviceHasAttr>()) {
11641  Diag(ExistingAttr->getLoc(), diag::warn_duplicate_attribute_exact) << &A;
11642  Diag(A.getLoc(), diag::note_previous_attribute);
11643  return nullptr;
11644  }
11645 
11646  SmallVector<Expr *, 5> Args;
11647  for (auto *E : A.aspects())
11648  Args.push_back(E);

11650  SYCLDeviceHasAttr(Context, A, Args.data(), Args.size());
11651 }

11653 void Sema::AddSYCLDeviceHasAttr(Decl *D, const AttributeCommonInfo &CI,
11654  Expr **Exprs, unsigned Size) {
11655 
11656  SYCLDeviceHasAttr TmpAttr(Context, CI, Exprs, Size);
11657  SmallVector<Expr *, 5> Aspects;
11658  for (auto *E : TmpAttr.aspects())
11659  if (!isa<PackExpansionExpr>(E) && !isDeviceAspectType(E->getType()))
11660  Diag(E->getExprLoc(), diag::err_sycl_invalid_aspect_argument) << CI;
11661 
11662  if (const auto *ExistingAttr = D->getAttr<SYCLDeviceHasAttr>()) {
11663  Diag(CI.getLoc(), diag::warn_duplicate_attribute_exact) << CI;
11664  Diag(ExistingAttr->getLoc(), diag::note_previous_attribute);
11665  return;
11666  }
11667 
11668  D->addAttr(::new (Context) SYCLDeviceHasAttr(Context, CI, Exprs, Size));
11669 }
11670 
11671 static void handleSYCLDeviceHasAttr(Sema &S, Decl *D, const ParsedAttr &A) {
11672  // Ignore the attribute if compiling for the host side because aspects may not
11673  // be marked properly for such compilation
11674  if (!S.Context.getLangOpts().SYCLIsDevice)
11675  return;
11676 
11677  SmallVector<Expr *, 5> Args;
11678  for (unsigned I = 0; I < A.getNumArgs(); ++I)
11679  Args.push_back(A.getArgAsExpr(I));
11680 
11681  S.AddSYCLDeviceHasAttr(D, A, Args.data(), Args.size());
11682 }
11683 
11684 SYCLUsesAspectsAttr *
11685 Sema::MergeSYCLUsesAspectsAttr(Decl *D, const SYCLUsesAspectsAttr &A) {
11686  if (const auto *ExistingAttr = D->getAttr<SYCLUsesAspectsAttr>()) {
11687  Diag(ExistingAttr->getLoc(), diag::warn_duplicate_attribute_exact) << &A;
11688  Diag(A.getLoc(), diag::note_previous_attribute);
11689  return nullptr;
11690  }
11691 
11692  SmallVector<Expr *, 5> Args;
11693  for (auto *E : A.aspects())
11694  Args.push_back(E);
11695  return ::new (Context)
11696  SYCLUsesAspectsAttr(Context, A, Args.data(), Args.size());
11697 }

11699 void Sema::AddSYCLUsesAspectsAttr(Decl *D, const AttributeCommonInfo &CI,
11700  Expr **Exprs, unsigned Size) {
11701 
11702  SYCLUsesAspectsAttr TmpAttr(Context, CI, Exprs, Size);
11703  SmallVector<Expr *, 5> Aspects;
11704  for (auto *E : TmpAttr.aspects())
11705  if (!isDeviceAspectType(E->getType()))
11706  Diag(E->getExprLoc(), diag::err_sycl_invalid_aspect_argument) << CI;
11707 
11708  if (const auto *ExistingAttr = D->getAttr<SYCLUsesAspectsAttr>()) {
11709  Diag(CI.getLoc(), diag::warn_duplicate_attribute_exact) << CI;
11710  Diag(ExistingAttr->getLoc(), diag::note_previous_attribute);
11711  return;
11712  }
11713 
11714  D->addAttr(::new (Context) SYCLUsesAspectsAttr(Context, CI, Exprs, Size));
11715 }

11717 static void handleSYCLUsesAspectsAttr(Sema &S, Decl *D, const ParsedAttr &A) {
11718  // Ignore the attribute if compiling for the host because aspects may not be
11719  // marked properly for such compilation
11720  if (!S.Context.getLangOpts().SYCLIsDevice)
11721  return;
11722 
11723  SmallVector<Expr *, 5> Args;
11724  for (unsigned I = 0; I < A.getNumArgs(); ++I)
11725  Args.push_back(A.getArgAsExpr(I));
11726 
11727  S.AddSYCLUsesAspectsAttr(D, A, Args.data(), Args.size());
11728 }

11750 static void handleSYCLKernelAttr(Sema &S, Decl *D, const ParsedAttr &AL) {
11751  // The 'sycl_kernel' attribute applies only to function templates.
11752  const auto *FD = cast<FunctionDecl>(D);
11753  const FunctionTemplateDecl *FT = FD->getDescribedFunctionTemplate();
11754  assert(FT && "Function template is expected");
11755 
11756  // Function template must have at least two template parameters so it
11757  // can be used in OpenCL kernel generation.
11758  const TemplateParameterList *TL = FT->getTemplateParameters();
11759  if (TL->size() < 2) {
11760  S.Diag(FT->getLocation(), diag::warn_sycl_kernel_num_of_template_params);
11761  return;
11762  }
11763 
11764  // The first two template parameters must be typenames.
11765  for (unsigned I = 0; I < 2 && I < TL->size(); ++I) {
11766  const NamedDecl *TParam = TL->getParam(I);
11767  if (isa<NonTypeTemplateParmDecl>(TParam)) {
11768  S.Diag(FT->getLocation(),
11769  diag::warn_sycl_kernel_invalid_template_param_type);
11770  return;
11771  }
11772  }
11773 
11774  // Function must have at least one parameter.
11775  if (getFunctionOrMethodNumParams(D) < 1) {
11776  S.Diag(FT->getLocation(), diag::warn_sycl_kernel_num_of_function_params);
11777  return;
11778  }
11779 
11780  // Function must return void.
11781  QualType RetTy = getFunctionOrMethodResultType(D);
11782  if (!RetTy->isVoidType()) {
11783  S.Diag(FT->getLocation(), diag::warn_sycl_kernel_return_type);
11784  return;
11785  }
11786 
11787  handleSimpleAttribute<SYCLKernelAttr>(S, D, AL);
11788 }

11790 SYCLTypeAttr *Sema::MergeSYCLTypeAttr(Decl *D, const AttributeCommonInfo &CI,
11791  SYCLTypeAttr::SYCLType TypeName) {
11792  if (const auto *ExistingAttr = D->getAttr<SYCLTypeAttr>()) {
11793  if (ExistingAttr->getType() != TypeName) {
11794  Diag(ExistingAttr->getLoc(), diag::err_duplicate_attribute)
11795  << ExistingAttr;
11796  Diag(CI.getLoc(), diag::note_previous_attribute);
11797  }
11798  // Do not add duplicate attribute
11799  return nullptr;
11800  }
11801  return ::new (Context) SYCLTypeAttr(Context, CI, TypeName);
11802 }

11804 static void handleSYCLTypeAttr(Sema &S, Decl *D, const ParsedAttr &AL) {
11805  if (!AL.isArgIdent(0)) {
11806  S.Diag(AL.getLoc(), diag::err_attribute_argument_type)
11807  << AL << AANT_ArgumentIdentifier;
11808  return;
11809  }

11812  SYCLTypeAttr::SYCLType Type;

11815  S.Diag(AL.getLoc(), diag::err_attribute_argument_not_supported) << AL << II;
11816  return;
11817  }
11818

11820  D->addAttr(NewAttr);

11823 static void handleDestroyAttr(Sema &S, Decl *D, const ParsedAttr &A) {

11841 
11842 static bool tryMakeVariablePseudoStrong(Sema &S, VarDecl *VD,
11843  bool DiagnoseFailure) {
11844  QualType Ty = VD->getType();
11845  if (!Ty->isObjCRetainableType()) {
11846  if (DiagnoseFailure) {
11847  S.Diag(VD->getBeginLoc(), diag::warn_ignored_objc_externally_retained)
11848  << 0;
11849  }
11850  return false;
11851  }
11852 
11853  Qualifiers::ObjCLifetime LifetimeQual = Ty.getQualifiers().getObjCLifetime();
11854 
11855  // Sema::inferObjCARCLifetime must run after processing decl attributes
11856  // (because __block lowers to an attribute), so if the lifetime hasn't been
11857  // explicitly specified, infer it locally now.
11858  if (LifetimeQual == Qualifiers::OCL_None)
11859  LifetimeQual = Ty->getObjCARCImplicitLifetime();
11860 
11861  // The attributes only really makes sense for __strong variables; ignore any
11862  // attempts to annotate a parameter with any other lifetime qualifier.
11863  if (LifetimeQual != Qualifiers::OCL_Strong) {
11864  if (DiagnoseFailure) {
11865  S.Diag(VD->getBeginLoc(), diag::warn_ignored_objc_externally_retained)
11866  << 1;
11867  }
11868  return false;
11869  }
11870 
11871  // Tampering with the type of a VarDecl here is a bit of a hack, but we need
11872  // to ensure that the variable is 'const' so that we can error on
11873  // modification, which can otherwise over-release.
11874  VD->setType(Ty.withConst());
11875  VD->setARCPseudoStrong(true);
11876  return true;
11877 }
11878 
11879 static void handleObjCExternallyRetainedAttr(Sema &S, Decl *D,
11880  const ParsedAttr &AL) {
11881  if (auto *VD = dyn_cast<VarDecl>(D)) {
11882  assert(!isa<ParmVarDecl>(VD) && "should be diagnosed automatically");
11883  if (!VD->hasLocalStorage()) {
11884  S.Diag(D->getBeginLoc(), diag::warn_ignored_objc_externally_retained)
11885  << 0;
11886  return;
11887  }
11888 
11889  if (!tryMakeVariablePseudoStrong(S, VD, /*DiagnoseFailure=*/true))
11890  return;
11891 
11892  handleSimpleAttribute<ObjCExternallyRetainedAttr>(S, D, AL);
11893  return;
11894  }
11895 
11896  // If D is a function-like declaration (method, block, or function), then we
11897  // make every parameter psuedo-strong.
11898  unsigned NumParams =
11899  hasFunctionProto(D) ? getFunctionOrMethodNumParams(D) : 0;
11900  for (unsigned I = 0; I != NumParams; ++I) {
11901  auto *PVD = const_cast<ParmVarDecl *>(getFunctionOrMethodParam(D, I));
11902  QualType Ty = PVD->getType();
11903 
11904  // If a user wrote a parameter with __strong explicitly, then assume they
11905  // want "real" strong semantics for that parameter. This works because if
11906  // the parameter was written with __strong, then the strong qualifier will
11907  // be non-local.
11908  if (Ty.getLocalUnqualifiedType().getQualifiers().getObjCLifetime() ==
11909  Qualifiers::OCL_Strong)
11910  continue;
11911 
11912  tryMakeVariablePseudoStrong(S, PVD, /*DiagnoseFailure=*/false);
11913  }
11914  handleSimpleAttribute<ObjCExternallyRetainedAttr>(S, D, AL);
11915 }
11916 
11917 static void handleMIGServerRoutineAttr(Sema &S, Decl *D, const ParsedAttr &AL) {
11918  // Check that the return type is a `typedef int kern_return_t` or a typedef
11919  // around it, because otherwise MIG convention checks make no sense.
11920  // BlockDecl doesn't store a return type, so it's annoying to check,
11921  // so let's skip it for now.
11922  if (!isa<BlockDecl>(D)) {
11923  QualType T = getFunctionOrMethodResultType(D);
11924  bool IsKernReturnT = false;
11925  while (const auto *TT = T->getAs<TypedefType>()) {
11926  IsKernReturnT = (TT->getDecl()->getName() == "kern_return_t");
11927  T = TT->desugar();
11928  }
11929  if (!IsKernReturnT || T.getCanonicalType() != S.getASTContext().IntTy) {
11930  S.Diag(D->getBeginLoc(),
11931  diag::warn_mig_server_routine_does_not_return_kern_return_t);
11932  return;
11933  }
11934  }
11935 
11936  handleSimpleAttribute<MIGServerRoutineAttr>(S, D, AL);
11937 }

11939 static void handleMSAllocatorAttr(Sema &S, Decl *D, const ParsedAttr &AL) {

11942  QualType RetTy = FD->getReturnType();
11943  if (!RetTy->isPointerType() && !RetTy->isReferenceType()) {
11944  S.Diag(AL.getLoc(), diag::warn_declspec_allocator_nonpointer)
11945  << AL.getRange() << RetTy;
11946  return;
11947  }
11948  }
11949 
11950  handleSimpleAttribute<MSAllocatorAttr>(S, D, AL);
11951 }

11958  if (PVD->getType()->isIntegerType()) {

11966  return;

11968 }

12003 template <typename AttrTy>
12004 static const AttrTy *findEnforceTCBAttrByName(Decl *D, StringRef Name) {
12005  auto Attrs = D->specific_attrs<AttrTy>();
12006  auto I = llvm::find_if(Attrs,
12007  [Name](const AttrTy *A) {
12008  return A->getTCBName() == Name;
12009  });
12010  return I == Attrs.end() ? nullptr : *I;
12011 }
12012 
12013 template <typename AttrTy, typename ConflictingAttrTy>
12014 static void handleEnforceTCBAttr(Sema &S, Decl *D, const ParsedAttr &AL) {
12015  StringRef Argument;
12016  if (!S.checkStringLiteralArgumentAttr(AL, 0, Argument))
12017  return;
12018 
12019  // A function cannot be have both regular and leaf membership in the same TCB.
12020  if (const ConflictingAttrTy *ConflictingAttr =
12021  findEnforceTCBAttrByName<ConflictingAttrTy>(D, Argument)) {
12022  // We could attach a note to the other attribute but in this case
12023  // there's no need given how the two are very close to each other.
12024  S.Diag(AL.getLoc(), diag::err_tcb_conflicting_attributes)
12025  << AL.getAttrName()->getName() << ConflictingAttr->getAttrName()->getName()
12026  << Argument;
12027 
12028  // Error recovery: drop the non-leaf attribute so that to suppress
12029  // all future warnings caused by erroneous attributes. The leaf attribute
12030  // needs to be kept because it can only suppresses warnings, not cause them.
12031  D->dropAttr<EnforceTCBAttr>();
12032  return;
12033  }
12034 
12035  D->addAttr(AttrTy::Create(S.Context, Argument, AL));
12036 }
12037 
12038 template <typename AttrTy, typename ConflictingAttrTy>
12039 static AttrTy *mergeEnforceTCBAttrImpl(Sema &S, Decl *D, const AttrTy &AL) {
12040  // Check if the new redeclaration has different leaf-ness in the same TCB.
12041  StringRef TCBName = AL.getTCBName();
12042  if (const ConflictingAttrTy *ConflictingAttr =
12043  findEnforceTCBAttrByName<ConflictingAttrTy>(D, TCBName)) {
12044  S.Diag(ConflictingAttr->getLoc(), diag::err_tcb_conflicting_attributes)
12045  << ConflictingAttr->getAttrName()->getName()
12046  << AL.getAttrName()->getName() << TCBName;
12047 
12048  // Add a note so that the user could easily find the conflicting attribute.
12049  S.Diag(AL.getLoc(), diag::note_conflicting_attribute);
12050 
12051  // More error recovery.
12052  D->dropAttr<EnforceTCBAttr>();
12053  return nullptr;
12054  }
12055 
12056  ASTContext &Context = S.getASTContext();
12057  return ::new(Context) AttrTy(Context, AL, AL.getTCBName());
12058 }
12059 
12060 EnforceTCBAttr *Sema::mergeEnforceTCBAttr(Decl *D, const EnforceTCBAttr &AL) {
12061  return mergeEnforceTCBAttrImpl<EnforceTCBAttr, EnforceTCBLeafAttr>(
12062  *this, D, AL);
12063 }
12064 
12065 EnforceTCBLeafAttr *Sema::mergeEnforceTCBLeafAttr(
12066  Decl *D, const EnforceTCBLeafAttr &AL) {
12067  return mergeEnforceTCBAttrImpl<EnforceTCBLeafAttr, EnforceTCBAttr>(
12068  *this, D, AL);
12069 }

12074 
12075 static bool IsDeclLambdaCallOperator(Decl *D) {
12076  if (const auto *MD = dyn_cast<CXXMethodDecl>(D))
12077  return MD->getParent()->isLambda() &&
12078  MD->getOverloadedOperator() == OverloadedOperatorKind::OO_Call;
12079  return false;
12080 }
12081 
12082 // Returns true if the attribute must delay setting its arguments until after
12083 // template instantiation, and false otherwise.
12084 static bool MustDelayAttributeArguments(const ParsedAttr &AL) {
12085  // Only attributes that accept expression parameter packs can delay arguments.
12086  if (!AL.acceptsExprPack())
12087  return false;
12088 
12089  bool AttrHasVariadicArg = AL.hasVariadicArg();
12090  unsigned AttrNumArgs = AL.getNumArgMembers();
12091  for (size_t I = 0; I < std::min(AL.getNumArgs(), AttrNumArgs); ++I) {
12092  bool IsLastAttrArg = I == (AttrNumArgs - 1);
12093  // If the argument is the last argument and it is variadic it can contain
12094  // any expression.
12095  if (IsLastAttrArg && AttrHasVariadicArg)
12096  return false;
12097  Expr *E = AL.getArgAsExpr(I);
12098  bool ArgMemberCanHoldExpr = AL.isParamExpr(I);
12099  // If the expression is a pack expansion then arguments must be delayed
12100  // unless the argument is an expression and it is the last argument of the
12101  // attribute.
12102  if (isa<PackExpansionExpr>(E))
12103  return !(IsLastAttrArg && ArgMemberCanHoldExpr);
12104  // Last case is if the expression is value dependent then it must delay
12105  // arguments unless the corresponding argument is able to hold the
12106  // expression.
12107  if (E->isValueDependent() && !ArgMemberCanHoldExpr)
12108  return true;
12109  }
12110  return false;
12111 }
12112 
12113 static bool checkArmNewAttrMutualExclusion(
12114  Sema &S, const ParsedAttr &AL, const FunctionProtoType *FPT,
12115  FunctionType::ArmStateValue CurrentState, StringRef StateName) {
12116  auto CheckForIncompatibleAttr =
12117  [&](FunctionType::ArmStateValue IncompatibleState,
12118  StringRef IncompatibleStateName) {
12119  if (CurrentState == IncompatibleState) {
12120  S.Diag(AL.getLoc(), diag::err_attributes_are_not_compatible)
12121  << (std::string("'__arm_new(\"") + StateName.str() + "\")'")
12122  << (std::string("'") + IncompatibleStateName.str() + "(\"" +
12123  StateName.str() + "\")'")
12124  << true;
12125  AL.setInvalid();
12126  }
12127  };
12128 
12129  CheckForIncompatibleAttr(FunctionType::ARM_In, "__arm_in");
12130  CheckForIncompatibleAttr(FunctionType::ARM_Out, "__arm_out");
12131  CheckForIncompatibleAttr(FunctionType::ARM_InOut, "__arm_inout");
12132  CheckForIncompatibleAttr(FunctionType::ARM_Preserves, "__arm_preserves");
12133  return AL.isInvalid();
12134 }
12135 
12136 static void handleArmNewAttr(Sema &S, Decl *D, const ParsedAttr &AL) {
12137  if (!AL.getNumArgs()) {
12138  S.Diag(AL.getLoc(), diag::err_missing_arm_state) << AL;
12139  AL.setInvalid();
12140  return;
12141  }
12142 
12143  std::vector<StringRef> NewState;
12144  if (const auto *ExistingAttr = D->getAttr<ArmNewAttr>()) {
12145  for (StringRef S : ExistingAttr->newArgs())
12146  NewState.push_back(S);
12147  }
12148 
12149  bool HasZA = false;
12150  bool HasZT0 = false;
12151  for (unsigned I = 0, E = AL.getNumArgs(); I != E; ++I) {
12152  StringRef StateName;
12153  SourceLocation LiteralLoc;
12154  if (!S.checkStringLiteralArgumentAttr(AL, I, StateName, &LiteralLoc))
12155  return;
12156 
12157  if (StateName == "za")
12158  HasZA = true;
12159  else if (StateName == "zt0")
12160  HasZT0 = true;
12161  else {
12162  S.Diag(LiteralLoc, diag::err_unknown_arm_state) << StateName;
12163  AL.setInvalid();
12164  return;
12165  }
12166 
12167  if (!llvm::is_contained(NewState, StateName)) // Avoid adding duplicates.
12168  NewState.push_back(StateName);
12169  }
12170 
12171  if (auto *FPT = dyn_cast<FunctionProtoType>(D->getFunctionType())) {
12172  FunctionType::ArmStateValue ZAState =
12173  FunctionType::getArmZAState(FPT->getAArch64SMEAttributes());
12174  if (HasZA && ZAState != FunctionType::ARM_None &&
12175  checkArmNewAttrMutualExclusion(S, AL, FPT, ZAState, "za"))
12176  return;
12177  FunctionType::ArmStateValue ZT0State =
12178  FunctionType::getArmZT0State(FPT->getAArch64SMEAttributes());
12179  if (HasZT0 && ZT0State != FunctionType::ARM_None &&
12180  checkArmNewAttrMutualExclusion(S, AL, FPT, ZT0State, "zt0"))
12181  return;
12182  }
12183 
12184  D->dropAttr<ArmNewAttr>();
12185  D->addAttr(::new (S.Context)
12186  ArmNewAttr(S.Context, AL, NewState.data(), NewState.size()));
12187 }
12188 
12189 /// ProcessDeclAttribute - Apply the specific attribute to the specified decl if
12190 /// the attribute applies to decls. If the attribute is a type attribute, just
12191 /// silently ignore it if a GNU attribute.
12192 static void
12193 ProcessDeclAttribute(Sema &S, Scope *scope, Decl *D, const ParsedAttr &AL,
12194  const Sema::ProcessDeclAttributeOptions &Options) {
12195  if (AL.isInvalid() || AL.getKind() == ParsedAttr::IgnoredAttribute)
12196  return;
12197 
12198  // Ignore C++11 attributes on declarator chunks: they appertain to the type
12199  // instead.
12200  if (AL.isCXX11Attribute() && !Options.IncludeCXX11Attributes &&
12201  (!IsDeclLambdaCallOperator(D) || !AL.supportsNonconformingLambdaSyntax()))
12202  return;
12203 
12204  // Unknown attributes are automatically warned on. Target-specific attributes
12205  // which do not apply to the current target architecture are treated as
12206  // though they were unknown attributes.
12207  const TargetInfo *Aux = S.Context.getAuxTargetInfo();
12208  if (AL.getKind() == ParsedAttr::UnknownAttribute ||
12209  !(AL.existsInTarget(S.Context.getTargetInfo()) ||
12210  (S.Context.getLangOpts().SYCLIsDevice &&
12211  Aux && AL.existsInTarget(*Aux)))) {
12212  S.Diag(AL.getLoc(),
12213  AL.isRegularKeywordAttribute()
12214  ? (unsigned)diag::err_keyword_not_supported_on_target
12215  : AL.isDeclspecAttribute()
12216  ? (unsigned)diag::warn_unhandled_ms_attribute_ignored
12217  : (unsigned)diag::warn_unknown_attribute_ignored)
12218  << AL << AL.getRange();
12219  return;
12220  }
12221 
12222  // Check if argument population must delayed to after template instantiation.
12223  bool MustDelayArgs = MustDelayAttributeArguments(AL);
12224 
12225  // Argument number check must be skipped if arguments are delayed.
12226  if (S.checkCommonAttributeFeatures(D, AL, MustDelayArgs))
12227  return;
12228 
12229  if (MustDelayArgs) {
12230  AL.handleAttrWithDelayedArgs(S, D);
12231  return;
12232  }
12233 
12234  switch (AL.getKind()) {
12235  default:
12236  if (AL.getInfo().handleDeclAttribute(S, D, AL) != ParsedAttrInfo::NotHandled)
12237  break;
12238  if (!AL.isStmtAttr()) {
12239  assert(AL.isTypeAttr() && "Non-type attribute not handled");
12240  }
12241  if (AL.isTypeAttr()) {
12242  if (Options.IgnoreTypeAttributes)
12243  break;
12244  if (!AL.isStandardAttributeSyntax() && !AL.isRegularKeywordAttribute()) {
12245  // Non-[[]] type attributes are handled in processTypeAttrs(); silently
12246  // move on.
12247  break;
12248  }
12249 
12250  // According to the C and C++ standards, we should never see a
12251  // [[]] type attribute on a declaration. However, we have in the past
12252  // allowed some type attributes to "slide" to the `DeclSpec`, so we need
12253  // to continue to support this legacy behavior. We only do this, however,
12254  // if
12255  // - we actually have a `DeclSpec`, i.e. if we're looking at a
12256  // `DeclaratorDecl`, or
12257  // - we are looking at an alias-declaration, where historically we have
12258  // allowed type attributes after the identifier to slide to the type.
12259  if (AL.slidesFromDeclToDeclSpecLegacyBehavior() &&
12260  isa<DeclaratorDecl, TypeAliasDecl>(D)) {
12261  // Suggest moving the attribute to the type instead, but only for our
12262  // own vendor attributes; moving other vendors' attributes might hurt
12263  // portability.
12264  if (AL.isClangScope()) {
12265  S.Diag(AL.getLoc(), diag::warn_type_attribute_deprecated_on_decl)
12266  << AL << D->getLocation();
12267  }
12268 
12269  // Allow this type attribute to be handled in processTypeAttrs();
12270  // silently move on.
12271  break;
12272  }
12273 
12274  if (AL.getKind() == ParsedAttr::AT_Regparm) {
12275  // `regparm` is a special case: It's a type attribute but we still want
12276  // to treat it as if it had been written on the declaration because that
12277  // way we'll be able to handle it directly in `processTypeAttr()`.
12278  // If we treated `regparm` it as if it had been written on the
12279  // `DeclSpec`, the logic in `distributeFunctionTypeAttrFromDeclSepc()`
12280  // would try to move it to the declarator, but that doesn't work: We
12281  // can't remove the attribute from the list of declaration attributes
12282  // because it might be needed by other declarators in the same
12283  // declaration.
12284  break;
12285  }
12286 
12287  if (AL.getKind() == ParsedAttr::AT_VectorSize) {
12288  // `vector_size` is a special case: It's a type attribute semantically,
12289  // but GCC expects the [[]] syntax to be written on the declaration (and
12290  // warns that the attribute has no effect if it is placed on the
12291  // decl-specifier-seq).
12292  // Silently move on and allow the attribute to be handled in
12293  // processTypeAttr().
12294  break;
12295  }
12296 
12297  if (AL.getKind() == ParsedAttr::AT_NoDeref) {
12298  // FIXME: `noderef` currently doesn't work correctly in [[]] syntax.
12299  // See https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/issues/55790 for details.
12300  // We allow processTypeAttrs() to emit a warning and silently move on.
12301  break;
12302  }
12303  }
12304  // N.B., ClangAttrEmitter.cpp emits a diagnostic helper that ensures a
12305  // statement attribute is not written on a declaration, but this code is
12306  // needed for type attributes as well as statement attributes in Attr.td
12307  // that do not list any subjects.
12308  S.Diag(AL.getLoc(), diag::err_attribute_invalid_on_decl)
12309  << AL << AL.isRegularKeywordAttribute() << D->getLocation();
12310  break;
12311  case ParsedAttr::AT_Interrupt:
12312  handleInterruptAttr(S, D, AL);
12313  break;
12314  case ParsedAttr::AT_X86ForceAlignArgPointer:
12315  handleX86ForceAlignArgPointerAttr(S, D, AL);
12316  break;
12317  case ParsedAttr::AT_ReadOnlyPlacement:
12318  handleSimpleAttribute<ReadOnlyPlacementAttr>(S, D, AL);
12319  break;

13141 
13142 /// ProcessDeclAttributeList - Apply all the decl attributes in the specified
13143 /// attribute list to the specified decl, ignoring any type attributes.
13144 void Sema::ProcessDeclAttributeList(
13145  Scope *S, Decl *D, const ParsedAttributesView &AttrList,
13146  const ProcessDeclAttributeOptions &Options) {
13147  if (AttrList.empty())
13148  return;
13149 
13150  for (const ParsedAttr &AL : AttrList)
13151  ProcessDeclAttribute(*this, S, D, AL, Options);
13152 
13153  // FIXME: We should be able to handle these cases in TableGen.
13154  // GCC accepts
13155  // static int a9 __attribute__((weakref));
13156  // but that looks really pointless. We reject it.
13157  if (D->hasAttr<WeakRefAttr>() && !D->hasAttr<AliasAttr>()) {
13158  Diag(AttrList.begin()->getLoc(), diag::err_attribute_weakref_without_alias)
13159  << cast<NamedDecl>(D);
13160  D->dropAttr<WeakRefAttr>();
13161  return;
13162  }
13163 
13164  // FIXME: We should be able to handle this in TableGen as well. It would be
13165  // good to have a way to specify "these attributes must appear as a group",
13166  // for these. Additionally, it would be good to have a way to specify "these
13167  // attribute must never appear as a group" for attributes like cold and hot.
13168  if (!(D->hasAttr<OpenCLKernelAttr>() ||
13169  LangOpts.SYCLIsDevice || LangOpts.SYCLIsHost)) {
13170  // These attributes cannot be applied to a non-kernel function.
13171  if (const auto *A = D->getAttr<ReqdWorkGroupSizeAttr>()) {
13172  // FIXME: This emits a different error message than
13173  // diag::err_attribute_wrong_decl_type + ExpectedKernelFunction.
13174  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::err_opencl_kernel_attr) << A;
13175  D->setInvalidDecl();
13176  } else if (const auto *A = D->getAttr<WorkGroupSizeHintAttr>()) {
13177  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::err_opencl_kernel_attr) << A;
13178  D->setInvalidDecl();
13179  } else if (const auto *A = D->getAttr<SYCLReqdWorkGroupSizeAttr>()) {
13180  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::err_opencl_kernel_attr) << A;
13181  D->setInvalidDecl();
13182  } else if (const auto *A = D->getAttr<SYCLWorkGroupSizeHintAttr>()) {
13183  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::err_opencl_kernel_attr) << A;
13184  D->setInvalidDecl();
13185  } else if (const auto *A = D->getAttr<SYCLIntelMaxWorkGroupSizeAttr>()) {
13186  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::err_opencl_kernel_attr) << A;
13187  D->setInvalidDecl();
13188  } else if (const auto *A =
13189  D->getAttr<SYCLIntelMinWorkGroupsPerComputeUnitAttr>()) {
13190  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::err_opencl_kernel_attr) << A;
13191  D->setInvalidDecl();
13192  } else if (const auto *A =
13193  D->getAttr<SYCLIntelMaxWorkGroupsPerMultiprocessorAttr>()) {
13194  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::err_opencl_kernel_attr) << A;
13195  D->setInvalidDecl();
13196  } else if (const auto *A = D->getAttr<SYCLIntelNoGlobalWorkOffsetAttr>()) {
13197  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::err_opencl_kernel_attr) << A;
13198  D->setInvalidDecl();
13199  } else if (const auto *A = D->getAttr<VecTypeHintAttr>()) {
13200  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::err_opencl_kernel_attr) << A;
13201  D->setInvalidDecl();
13202  } else if (const auto *A = D->getAttr<IntelReqdSubGroupSizeAttr>()) {
13203  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::err_opencl_kernel_attr) << A;
13204  D->setInvalidDecl();
13205  } else if (!D->hasAttr<CUDAGlobalAttr>()) {
13206  if (const auto *A = D->getAttr<AMDGPUFlatWorkGroupSizeAttr>()) {
13207  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::err_attribute_wrong_decl_type)
13208  << A << A->isRegularKeywordAttribute() << ExpectedKernelFunction;
13209  D->setInvalidDecl();
13210  } else if (const auto *A = D->getAttr<AMDGPUWavesPerEUAttr>()) {
13211  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::err_attribute_wrong_decl_type)
13212  << A << A->isRegularKeywordAttribute() << ExpectedKernelFunction;
13213  D->setInvalidDecl();
13214  } else if (const auto *A = D->getAttr<AMDGPUNumSGPRAttr>()) {
13215  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::err_attribute_wrong_decl_type)
13216  << A << A->isRegularKeywordAttribute() << ExpectedKernelFunction;
13217  D->setInvalidDecl();
13218  } else if (const auto *A = D->getAttr<AMDGPUNumVGPRAttr>()) {
13219  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::err_attribute_wrong_decl_type)
13220  << A << A->isRegularKeywordAttribute() << ExpectedKernelFunction;
13221  D->setInvalidDecl();
13222  }
13223  }
13224  }
13225 
13226  // Do this check after processing D's attributes because the attribute
13227  // objc_method_family can change whether the given method is in the init
13228  // family, and it can be applied after objc_designated_initializer. This is a
13229  // bit of a hack, but we need it to be compatible with versions of clang that
13230  // processed the attribute list in the wrong order.
13231  if (D->hasAttr<ObjCDesignatedInitializerAttr>() &&
13232  cast<ObjCMethodDecl>(D)->getMethodFamily() != OMF_init) {
13233  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::err_designated_init_attr_non_init);
13234  D->dropAttr<ObjCDesignatedInitializerAttr>();
13235  }
13236 }
13237 
13238 // Helper for delayed processing TransparentUnion or BPFPreserveAccessIndexAttr
13239 // attribute.
13240 void Sema::ProcessDeclAttributeDelayed(Decl *D,
13241  const ParsedAttributesView &AttrList) {
13242  for (const ParsedAttr &AL : AttrList)
13243  if (AL.getKind() == ParsedAttr::AT_TransparentUnion) {
13244  handleTransparentUnionAttr(*this, D, AL);
13245  break;
13246  }
13247 
13248  // For BPFPreserveAccessIndexAttr, we want to populate the attributes
13249  // to fields and inner records as well.
13250  if (D && D->hasAttr<BPFPreserveAccessIndexAttr>())
13251  handleBPFPreserveAIRecord(*this, cast<RecordDecl>(D));
13252 }
13253 
13254 // Annotation attributes are the only attributes allowed after an access
13255 // specifier.
13256 bool Sema::ProcessAccessDeclAttributeList(
13257  AccessSpecDecl *ASDecl, const ParsedAttributesView &AttrList) {
13258  for (const ParsedAttr &AL : AttrList) {
13259  if (AL.getKind() == ParsedAttr::AT_Annotate) {
13260  ProcessDeclAttribute(*this, nullptr, ASDecl, AL,
13261  ProcessDeclAttributeOptions());
13262  } else {
13263  Diag(AL.getLoc(), diag::err_only_annotate_after_access_spec);
13264  return true;
13265  }
13266  }
13267  return false;
13268 }
13269 
13270 /// checkUnusedDeclAttributes - Check a list of attributes to see if it
13271 /// contains any decl attributes that we should warn about.
13272 static void checkUnusedDeclAttributes(Sema &S, const ParsedAttributesView &A) {
13273  for (const ParsedAttr &AL : A) {
13274  // Only warn if the attribute is an unignored, non-type attribute.
13275  if (AL.isUsedAsTypeAttr() || AL.isInvalid())
13276  continue;
13277  if (AL.getKind() == ParsedAttr::IgnoredAttribute)
13278  continue;
13279 
13280  if (AL.getKind() == ParsedAttr::UnknownAttribute) {
13281  S.Diag(AL.getLoc(), diag::warn_unknown_attribute_ignored)
13282  << AL << AL.getRange();
13283  } else {
13284  S.Diag(AL.getLoc(), diag::warn_attribute_not_on_decl) << AL
13285  << AL.getRange();
13286  }
13287  }
13288 }
13289 
13290 /// checkUnusedDeclAttributes - Given a declarator which is not being
13291 /// used to build a declaration, complain about any decl attributes
13292 /// which might be lying around on it.
13293 void Sema::checkUnusedDeclAttributes(Declarator &D) {
13294  ::checkUnusedDeclAttributes(*this, D.getDeclarationAttributes());
13295  ::checkUnusedDeclAttributes(*this, D.getDeclSpec().getAttributes());
13296  ::checkUnusedDeclAttributes(*this, D.getAttributes());
13297  for (unsigned i = 0, e = D.getNumTypeObjects(); i != e; ++i)
13298  ::checkUnusedDeclAttributes(*this, D.getTypeObject(i).getAttrs());
13299 }
13300 
13301 /// DeclClonePragmaWeak - clone existing decl (maybe definition),
13302 /// \#pragma weak needs a non-definition decl and source may not have one.
13303 NamedDecl *Sema::DeclClonePragmaWeak(NamedDecl *ND, const IdentifierInfo *II,
13304  SourceLocation Loc) {
13305  assert(isa<FunctionDecl>(ND) || isa<VarDecl>(ND));
13306  NamedDecl *NewD = nullptr;
13307  if (auto *FD = dyn_cast<FunctionDecl>(ND)) {
13308  FunctionDecl *NewFD;
13309  // FIXME: Missing call to CheckFunctionDeclaration().
13310  // FIXME: Mangling?
13311  // FIXME: Is the qualifier info correct?
13312  // FIXME: Is the DeclContext correct?
13313  NewFD = FunctionDecl::Create(
13314  FD->getASTContext(), FD->getDeclContext(), Loc, Loc,
13315  DeclarationName(II), FD->getType(), FD->getTypeSourceInfo(), SC_None,
13316  getCurFPFeatures().isFPConstrained(), false /*isInlineSpecified*/,
13317  FD->hasPrototype(), ConstexprSpecKind::Unspecified,
13318  FD->getTrailingRequiresClause());
13319  NewD = NewFD;
13320 
13321  if (FD->getQualifier())
13322  NewFD->setQualifierInfo(FD->getQualifierLoc());
13323 
13324  // Fake up parameter variables; they are declared as if this were
13325  // a typedef.
13326  QualType FDTy = FD->getType();
13327  if (const auto *FT = FDTy->getAs<FunctionProtoType>()) {
13328  SmallVector<ParmVarDecl*, 16> Params;
13329  for (const auto &AI : FT->param_types()) {
13330  ParmVarDecl *Param = BuildParmVarDeclForTypedef(NewFD, Loc, AI);
13331  Param->setScopeInfo(0, Params.size());
13332  Params.push_back(Param);
13333  }
13334  NewFD->setParams(Params);
13335  }
13336  } else if (auto *VD = dyn_cast<VarDecl>(ND)) {
13337  NewD = VarDecl::Create(VD->getASTContext(), VD->getDeclContext(),
13338  VD->getInnerLocStart(), VD->getLocation(), II,
13339  VD->getType(), VD->getTypeSourceInfo(),
13340  VD->getStorageClass());
13341  if (VD->getQualifier())
13342  cast<VarDecl>(NewD)->setQualifierInfo(VD->getQualifierLoc());
13343  }
13344  return NewD;
13345 }
13346 
13347 /// DeclApplyPragmaWeak - A declaration (maybe definition) needs \#pragma weak
13348 /// applied to it, possibly with an alias.
13349 void Sema::DeclApplyPragmaWeak(Scope *S, NamedDecl *ND, const WeakInfo &W) {
13350  if (W.getAlias()) { // clone decl, impersonate __attribute(weak,alias(...))
13351  IdentifierInfo *NDId = ND->getIdentifier();
13352  NamedDecl *NewD = DeclClonePragmaWeak(ND, W.getAlias(), W.getLocation());
13353  NewD->addAttr(
13354  AliasAttr::CreateImplicit(Context, NDId->getName(), W.getLocation()));
13355  NewD->addAttr(WeakAttr::CreateImplicit(Context, W.getLocation()));
13356  WeakTopLevelDecl.push_back(NewD);
13357  // FIXME: "hideous" code from Sema::LazilyCreateBuiltin
13358  // to insert Decl at TU scope, sorry.
13359  DeclContext *SavedContext = CurContext;
13360  CurContext = Context.getTranslationUnitDecl();
13361  NewD->setDeclContext(CurContext);
13362  NewD->setLexicalDeclContext(CurContext);
13363  PushOnScopeChains(NewD, S);
13364  CurContext = SavedContext;
13365  } else { // just add weak to existing
13366  ND->addAttr(WeakAttr::CreateImplicit(Context, W.getLocation()));
13367  }
13368 }
13369 
13370 void Sema::ProcessPragmaWeak(Scope *S, Decl *D) {
13371  // It's valid to "forward-declare" #pragma weak, in which case we
13372  // have to do this.
13373  LoadExternalWeakUndeclaredIdentifiers();
13374  if (WeakUndeclaredIdentifiers.empty())
13375  return;
13376  NamedDecl *ND = nullptr;
13377  if (auto *VD = dyn_cast<VarDecl>(D))
13378  if (VD->isExternC())
13379  ND = VD;
13380  if (auto *FD = dyn_cast<FunctionDecl>(D))
13381  if (FD->isExternC())
13382  ND = FD;
13383  if (!ND)
13384  return;
13385  if (IdentifierInfo *Id = ND->getIdentifier()) {
13386  auto I = WeakUndeclaredIdentifiers.find(Id);
13387  if (I != WeakUndeclaredIdentifiers.end()) {
13388  auto &WeakInfos = I->second;
13389  for (const auto &W : WeakInfos)
13390  DeclApplyPragmaWeak(S, ND, W);
13391  std::remove_reference_t<decltype(WeakInfos)> EmptyWeakInfos;
13392  WeakInfos.swap(EmptyWeakInfos);
13393  }
13394  }
13395 }
13396 
13397 /// ProcessDeclAttributes - Given a declarator (PD) with attributes indicated in
13398 /// it, apply them to D. This is a bit tricky because PD can have attributes
13399 /// specified in many different places, and we need to find and apply them all.
13400 void Sema::ProcessDeclAttributes(Scope *S, Decl *D, const Declarator &PD) {
13401  // Ordering of attributes can be important, so we take care to process
13402  // attributes in the order in which they appeared in the source code.
13403 
13404  // First, process attributes that appeared on the declaration itself (but
13405  // only if they don't have the legacy behavior of "sliding" to the DeclSepc).
13406  ParsedAttributesView NonSlidingAttrs;
13407  for (ParsedAttr &AL : PD.getDeclarationAttributes()) {
13408  if (AL.slidesFromDeclToDeclSpecLegacyBehavior()) {
13409  // Skip processing the attribute, but do check if it appertains to the
13410  // declaration. This is needed for the `MatrixType` attribute, which,
13411  // despite being a type attribute, defines a `SubjectList` that only
13412  // allows it to be used on typedef declarations.
13413  AL.diagnoseAppertainsTo(*this, D);
13414  } else {
13415  NonSlidingAttrs.addAtEnd(&AL);
13416  }
13417  }
13418  ProcessDeclAttributeList(S, D, NonSlidingAttrs);
13419 
13420  // Apply decl attributes from the DeclSpec if present.
13421  if (!PD.getDeclSpec().getAttributes().empty()) {
13422  ProcessDeclAttributeList(S, D, PD.getDeclSpec().getAttributes(),
13423  ProcessDeclAttributeOptions()
13424  .WithIncludeCXX11Attributes(false)
13425  .WithIgnoreTypeAttributes(true));
13426  }
13427 
13428  // Walk the declarator structure, applying decl attributes that were in a type
13429  // position to the decl itself. This handles cases like:
13430  // int *__attr__(x)** D;
13431  // when X is a decl attribute.
13432  for (unsigned i = 0, e = PD.getNumTypeObjects(); i != e; ++i) {
13433  ProcessDeclAttributeList(S, D, PD.getTypeObject(i).getAttrs(),
13434  ProcessDeclAttributeOptions()
13435  .WithIncludeCXX11Attributes(false)
13436  .WithIgnoreTypeAttributes(true));
13437  }
13438 
13439  // Finally, apply any attributes on the decl itself.
13440  ProcessDeclAttributeList(S, D, PD.getAttributes());
13441 
13442  // Apply additional attributes specified by '#pragma clang attribute'.
13443  AddPragmaAttributes(S, D);
13444 
13445  // Look for API notes that map to attributes.
13446  ProcessAPINotes(D);
13447 }
13448 
13449 /// Is the given declaration allowed to use a forbidden type?
13450 /// If so, it'll still be annotated with an attribute that makes it
13451 /// illegal to actually use.
13452 static bool isForbiddenTypeAllowed(Sema &S, Decl *D,
13453  const DelayedDiagnostic &diag,
13454  UnavailableAttr::ImplicitReason &reason) {
13455  // Private ivars are always okay. Unfortunately, people don't
13456  // always properly make their ivars private, even in system headers.
13457  // Plus we need to make fields okay, too.
13458  if (!isa<FieldDecl>(D) && !isa<ObjCPropertyDecl>(D) &&
13459  !isa<FunctionDecl>(D))
13460  return false;
13461 
13462  // Silently accept unsupported uses of __weak in both user and system
13463  // declarations when it's been disabled, for ease of integration with
13464  // -fno-objc-arc files. We do have to take some care against attempts
13465  // to define such things; for now, we've only done that for ivars
13466  // and properties.
13467  if ((isa<ObjCIvarDecl>(D) || isa<ObjCPropertyDecl>(D))) {
13468  if (diag.getForbiddenTypeDiagnostic() == diag::err_arc_weak_disabled ||
13469  diag.getForbiddenTypeDiagnostic() == diag::err_arc_weak_no_runtime) {
13470  reason = UnavailableAttr::IR_ForbiddenWeak;
13471  return true;
13472  }
13473  }
13474 
13475  // Allow all sorts of things in system headers.
13476  if (S.Context.getSourceManager().isInSystemHeader(D->getLocation())) {
13477  // Currently, all the failures dealt with this way are due to ARC
13478  // restrictions.
13479  reason = UnavailableAttr::IR_ARCForbiddenType;
13480  return true;
13481  }
13482 
13483  return false;
13484 }
13485 
13486 /// Handle a delayed forbidden-type diagnostic.
13487 static void handleDelayedForbiddenType(Sema &S, DelayedDiagnostic &DD,
13488  Decl *D) {
13489  auto Reason = UnavailableAttr::IR_None;
13490  if (D && isForbiddenTypeAllowed(S, D, DD, Reason)) {
13491  assert(Reason && "didn't set reason?");
13492  D->addAttr(UnavailableAttr::CreateImplicit(S.Context, "", Reason, DD.Loc));
13493  return;
13494  }
13495  if (S.getLangOpts().ObjCAutoRefCount)
13496  if (const auto *FD = dyn_cast<FunctionDecl>(D)) {
13497  // FIXME: we may want to suppress diagnostics for all
13498  // kind of forbidden type messages on unavailable functions.
13499  if (FD->hasAttr<UnavailableAttr>() &&
13500  DD.getForbiddenTypeDiagnostic() ==
13501  diag::err_arc_array_param_no_ownership) {
13502  DD.Triggered = true;
13503  return;
13504  }
13505  }
13506 
13507  S.Diag(DD.Loc, DD.getForbiddenTypeDiagnostic())
13508  << DD.getForbiddenTypeOperand() << DD.getForbiddenTypeArgument();
13509  DD.Triggered = true;
13510 }
13511 
13512 
13513 void Sema::PopParsingDeclaration(ParsingDeclState state, Decl *decl) {
13514  assert(DelayedDiagnostics.getCurrentPool());
13515  DelayedDiagnosticPool &poppedPool = *DelayedDiagnostics.getCurrentPool();
13516  DelayedDiagnostics.popWithoutEmitting(state);
13517 
13518  // When delaying diagnostics to run in the context of a parsed
13519  // declaration, we only want to actually emit anything if parsing
13520  // succeeds.
13521  if (!decl) return;
13522 
13523  // We emit all the active diagnostics in this pool or any of its
13524  // parents. In general, we'll get one pool for the decl spec
13525  // and a child pool for each declarator; in a decl group like:
13526  // deprecated_typedef foo, *bar, baz();
13527  // only the declarator pops will be passed decls. This is correct;
13528  // we really do need to consider delayed diagnostics from the decl spec
13529  // for each of the different declarations.
13530  const DelayedDiagnosticPool *pool = &poppedPool;
13531  do {
13532  bool AnyAccessFailures = false;
13533  for (DelayedDiagnosticPool::pool_iterator
13534  i = pool->pool_begin(), e = pool->pool_end(); i != e; ++i) {
13535  // This const_cast is a bit lame. Really, Triggered should be mutable.
13536  DelayedDiagnostic &diag = const_cast<DelayedDiagnostic&>(*i);
13537  if (diag.Triggered)
13538  continue;
13539 
13540  switch (diag.Kind) {
13541  case DelayedDiagnostic::Availability:
13542  // Don't bother giving deprecation/unavailable diagnostics if
13543  // the decl is invalid.
13544  if (!decl->isInvalidDecl())
13545  handleDelayedAvailabilityCheck(diag, decl);
13546  break;
13547 
13548  case DelayedDiagnostic::Access:
13549  // Only produce one access control diagnostic for a structured binding
13550  // declaration: we don't need to tell the user that all the fields are
13551  // inaccessible one at a time.
13552  if (AnyAccessFailures && isa<DecompositionDecl>(decl))
13553  continue;
13554  HandleDelayedAccessCheck(diag, decl);
13555  if (diag.Triggered)
13556  AnyAccessFailures = true;
13557  break;
13558 
13559  case DelayedDiagnostic::ForbiddenType:
13560  handleDelayedForbiddenType(*this, diag, decl);
13561  break;
13562  }
13563  }
13564  } while ((pool = pool->getParent()));
13565 }
13566 
13567 /// Given a set of delayed diagnostics, re-emit them as if they had
13568 /// been delayed in the current context instead of in the given pool.
13569 /// Essentially, this just moves them to the current pool.
13570 void Sema::redelayDiagnostics(DelayedDiagnosticPool &pool) {
13571  DelayedDiagnosticPool *curPool = DelayedDiagnostics.getCurrentPool();
13572  assert(curPool && "re-emitting in undelayed context not supported");
13573  curPool->steal(pool);
13574 }
